    <Data><![CDATA[<h1>Applies to</h1>
  <p>Scala and Play Framework 2.1.0+<br /></p>
  <h1>What to Do</h1>
  <p>Make inactive sessions time-out.</p>
  <h1>Why</h1>
  <p>Make sessions expire after a period of inactivity to make it harder for an attacker to hijack a session.</p>
  <h1>How</h1>
  <p />
  <p>To make inactive sessions time-out:</p>
  <ol>
    <li>
      <p>
        <strong>Identify login functionality.</strong>&amp;nbsp;Find code that handles user logins.</p>
    </li>
    <li>
      <p>
        <strong>Add code that sets the inactive session time-out period.</strong>&amp;nbsp;There is no technical timeout for the Session. It expires when the user closes the web browser.&amp;nbsp;</p>
      <p>If you need a functional timeout for a specific application, store a timestamp into the user Session and use it in the way your application needs (e.g. for a maximum session duration, maximum inactivity duration, etc.).&amp;nbsp;<a href="https://github.com/jroper/play-security-utils/">This</a>&amp;nbsp;link explains how to add session timeout functionality to the application.&amp;nbsp;</p>
    </li>
  </ol>
  <h1>Additional Resources</h1>
  <ul>
    <li>For more information about the&amp;nbsp;method, please see<a href="http://download.oracle.com/javaee/6/api/javax/servlet/http/HttpSession.html#setMaxInactiveInterval%28int%29">:</a>&amp;nbsp;<a href="https://github.com/jroper/play-security-utils/blob/master/src/main/scala/play/security/utils/SessionTimeoutAction.scala">https://github.com/jroper/play-security-utils/blob/master/src/main/scala/play/security/utils/SessionTimeoutAction.scala</a></li>
  </ul>
